	painsBodyHtml={`<p>It's a strange ache: you're surrounded by more people than ever — roommates, classes, parties, group chats — and still feel like nobody really knows you. You're free for the first time, and the freedom can feel like fog: no one telling you who to be, and no one to come home to at night. The pressure to perform, to have it figured out, to seem fine, runs constant.</p><p>And then there's faith. For a lot of students, college is where the childhood version of God quietly falls apart — and no one warns you that doubt isn't the same as walking away. These aren't signs that something is wrong with you. They're the marks of a real human being in a real season of upheaval. And there is a Father in the middle of it who never moved.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `American College Health Association / BestColleges — student mental health`, url: `https://www.bestcolleges.com/research/college-student-mental-health-statistics/` },
		{ label: `Trellis Strategies — student loneliness research brief (2024)`, url: `https://www.trellisstrategies.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Research-Brief_TSFEB26_Loneliness.pdf` },
		{ label: `Lifeway Research — young adults leaving the church`, url: `https://research.lifeway.com/2019/01/15/most-teenagers-drop-out-of-church-as-young-adults/` },
