	faqs={[
		{ question: `What are good Bible verses for college students?`, answer: `Luke 15:20 (the father runs to the prodigal), Jeremiah 29:11 (plans for a future and a hope), Psalm 139:14 (fearfully and wonderfully made), Romans 8:38-39 (nothing can separate us from God's love), Matthew 11:28 (come to Me and rest), John 1:12 (the right to become children of God), Isaiah 43:1 (called by name, you are Mine), and Philippians 4:6 (do not be anxious) all speak straight to a student's season. Read and hear them free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about anxiety in college?`, answer: `Scripture takes anxiety seriously and offers a place to put it. Philippians 4:6 says don't be anxious about anything, but bring every request to your Father; Matthew 11:28 invites the weary and burdened to come and find rest; and 1 Peter 5:7 says cast your anxiety on Him because He cares for you. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you can read these free, with audio, and meet the Father who isn't overwhelmed by what overwhelms you.` },
		{ question: `What if I'm losing my faith in college?`, answer: `You're in a very common season, and doubt is not the same as walking away. Many students find that a childhood picture of God falls apart in college so a truer one can take its place. Romans 8:38-39 promises nothing — not even your hardest questions — can separate you from God's love, and Luke 15 shows a Father who runs to welcome a child back. The Father's Heart Bible™ lets you read these passages free and meet God as a Father you can bring your real questions to.` },
		{ question: `Is there a free online Bible with audio for students?`, answer: `Yes. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online — no account, no purchase, no app. Open fathersheartbible.com/read on any phone or laptop and read or hear any book — perfect for listening on the walk to class or reading a few minutes before bed.` },
		{ question: `How can I find my identity in God instead of my grades?`, answer: `Start by hearing who God says you are. Psalm 139:14 says you are fearfully and wonderfully made, John 1:12 calls you a child of God, and Isaiah 43:1 says you are called by name and you are His — none of it tied to your GPA or your resume. Reading the Father's Heart Bible™ daily, where God is revealed as Father, helps anchor your worth in His delight rather than your performance.` },
		{ question: `What makes the Father's Heart Bible™ different for college students?`, answer: `It is the first English translation to reveal God as Father wherever Scripture reveals Him as Father — so the God you read has a Father's face, not a rule-keeper's. For a student rebuilding faith away from home, that reframes everything: you come to the text first as a beloved child being fathered, not a performer being graded.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about feeling lonely at college?`, answer: `Even surrounded by people, students often feel unseen — and Scripture speaks right into it. Isaiah 43:1 says God calls you by name and you are His, John 14:18 promises 'I will not leave you as orphans,' and Psalm 139 says you are fully known wherever you are. Read free with audio in the Father's Heart Bible™, these verses point to a Father who is present and who knows your actual name in a sea of strangers.` },
	]}
